1
00:00:05,772 --> 00:00:07,340
Previously on "ER.."

2
00:00:07,373 --> 00:00:09,175
‐ Want a bite?
‐ No, I'll just watch you eat.

3
00:00:09,209 --> 00:00:10,210
‐ Where's that going?
‐ What do you mean?

4
00:00:10,243 --> 00:00:11,244
You and the desk clerk?

5
00:00:11,277 --> 00:00:12,312
'Would your grandmother'

6
00:00:12,345 --> 00:00:13,647
consider this clinic idea?

7
00:00:13,680 --> 00:00:14,781
She'd probably look at it.

8
00:00:14,815 --> 00:00:16,416
After I pay my landlord

9
00:00:16,449 --> 00:00:19,319
the med school bills,
my phone bill, the gas bill

10
00:00:19,352 --> 00:00:20,521
that should leave me
about four bucks.

11
00:00:20,554 --> 00:00:21,755
Oh, yeah. Me, too.

12
00:00:21,788 --> 00:00:23,356
You've not worked
with Dr. Romano?

13
00:00:23,389 --> 00:00:24,457
Rocket Romano?

14
00:00:24,490 --> 00:00:25,792
Rocket's sponsoring my BTA.

15
00:00:25,826 --> 00:00:29,362
‐ Damn you people!
‐ You son of a bitch!

16
00:00:29,395 --> 00:00:30,531
That's enough!

17
00:00:30,564 --> 00:00:32,799
Believe me,
it won't get any better.

18
00:00:32,833 --> 00:00:34,367
You belong in jail.

19
00:00:34,400 --> 00:00:35,736
I wish it was me
who kicked your white ass.

20
00:00:44,277 --> 00:00:45,445
I hope I didn't wake you.

21
00:00:45,478 --> 00:00:48,448
No. No.
I smelled the coffee.

22
00:00:48,481 --> 00:00:51,184
Oh, well, uh,
let me get you a cup.

23
00:00:51,217 --> 00:00:52,586
Okay.

24
00:00:54,320 --> 00:00:55,722
You're cheerful
this morning.

25
00:00:57,423 --> 00:00:59,159
Did you talk to
the foreman yet?

26
00:00:59,192 --> 00:01:02,362
Yeah, yeah. He gave me
the same old, same old.

27
00:01:02,395 --> 00:01:04,264
All crewed up.

28
00:01:04,297 --> 00:01:05,866
But I talked
to Tommy Styles.

29
00:01:05,899 --> 00:01:07,868
Tommy styles? I thought
he moved to Atlanta.

30
00:01:07,901 --> 00:01:10,370
Yeah, he's a
general manager

31
00:01:10,403 --> 00:01:12,873
of a construction
company down there

32
00:01:12,906 --> 00:01:15,676
that got some contracts
during the Olympics

33
00:01:15,709 --> 00:01:18,144
and, uh...

34
00:01:18,178 --> 00:01:21,281
things just grew
from there, and..

35
00:01:21,314 --> 00:01:23,416
...they can't get enough
guys to fill their gigs.

36
00:01:23,449 --> 00:01:24,618
Good for him.

37
00:01:24,651 --> 00:01:26,587
Yeah.
He said, uh..

38
00:01:26,620 --> 00:01:29,756
He said a guy with
my skills could..

39
00:01:29,790 --> 00:01:33,359
...make some real good
money the first year out.

40
00:01:33,393 --> 00:01:34,561
In Atlanta?

41
00:01:34,595 --> 00:01:36,229
Yeah.

42
00:01:36,262 --> 00:01:39,332
I mean, it could be
a chance for a fresh start.

43
00:01:39,365 --> 00:01:41,367
Better job
opportunities

44
00:01:41,401 --> 00:01:43,136
better weather.

45
00:01:43,169 --> 00:01:45,672
We already know Tommy,
my sister's down there..

46
00:01:45,706 --> 00:01:47,874
...and it's a chocolate city

47
00:01:47,908 --> 00:01:48,909
so socially‐‐

48
00:01:48,942 --> 00:01:50,711
Sounds great.

49
00:01:50,744 --> 00:01:51,745
But..?

50
00:01:51,778 --> 00:01:53,313
But we're not kids anymore.

51
00:01:53,346 --> 00:01:54,615
We can't just start over.

52
00:01:54,648 --> 00:01:56,517
Why not? Hmm?
Why not?

53
00:01:56,550 --> 00:01:58,284
Why can't we just
wipe the slate clean?

54
00:01:58,318 --> 00:02:01,454
Because we have a mortgage
and I have a job.

55
00:02:01,487 --> 00:02:03,356
But I don't.

56
00:02:03,389 --> 00:02:06,893
You know, I'm being
frozen out up here

57
00:02:06,927 --> 00:02:08,161
and after that
fight with Bill

58
00:02:08,194 --> 00:02:10,396
I can't just hang out

59
00:02:10,430 --> 00:02:13,867
and watch the football game
with the guys.

60
00:02:13,900 --> 00:02:16,903
My life is over
up here.

61
00:02:16,937 --> 00:02:19,405
In Atlanta..

62
00:02:19,439 --> 00:02:20,841
...we wouldn't have
to tell anybody.

63
00:02:20,874 --> 00:02:22,809
Nobody would know.

64
00:02:26,580 --> 00:02:27,881
Hey. How many patients
do you think

65
00:02:27,914 --> 00:02:29,550
we see in the hospital
every year?

66
00:02:29,583 --> 00:02:31,351
Too many.

67
00:02:31,384 --> 00:02:32,919
'Could you be a little
more specific?'

68
00:02:32,953 --> 00:02:35,689
‐ It's for my grant proposal.
‐ Uh‐huh, that's right.

69
00:02:35,722 --> 00:02:38,559
Tonight's the Carter family
foundation night. You nervous?

70
00:02:38,592 --> 00:02:40,326
No, I figure the worse
she can say is no.

71
00:02:40,360 --> 00:02:42,362
And then I'm back where I
started, clueless and penniless.

72
00:02:42,395 --> 00:02:44,865
‐ Good morning, all.
‐ Hey. You in a good mood?

73
00:02:44,898 --> 00:02:47,901
Well, the hospital settled
the Kenny Law malpractice suit.

74
00:02:47,934 --> 00:02:50,971
No more process servers,
no more depositions

75
00:02:51,004 --> 00:02:53,273
and after today,
no more work

76
00:02:53,306 --> 00:02:56,777
because I've got three days
of vacation time before me.

77
00:02:56,810 --> 00:02:57,811
Any plans?

78
00:02:57,844 --> 00:02:59,980
Uh, sleep, sleep
and sleep.

79
00:03:00,013 --> 00:03:01,447
Mark, how many patients
do you think

80
00:03:01,481 --> 00:03:02,816
we see in the hospital
every year?

81
00:03:02,849 --> 00:03:05,752
Oh, would that be real
patients or turkeys?

82
00:03:05,786 --> 00:03:07,420
Forget I asked.

83
00:03:07,453 --> 00:03:10,524
Look, your count will
be about 95 percent higher

84
00:03:10,557 --> 00:03:12,458
if you count
all the wackos.

85
00:03:12,492 --> 00:03:13,827
It's a little harsh.

86
00:03:13,860 --> 00:03:15,228
Alright, Carol,
I'll make you a wager.

87
00:03:15,261 --> 00:03:16,663
Uh‐huh. Uh.

88
00:03:16,697 --> 00:03:18,799
A wager on
the turkey‐to‐patient ratio

89
00:03:18,832 --> 00:03:19,866
over the next 12 hours.

90
00:03:19,900 --> 00:03:21,234
‐ No, thanks.
‐ Come on.

91
00:03:21,267 --> 00:03:22,268
I'll give you
two‐to‐one odds.

92
00:03:22,302 --> 00:03:23,870
Can I get a doctor quickly?

93
00:03:23,904 --> 00:03:26,339
Help, please? Anyone?

94
00:03:26,372 --> 00:03:28,274
You see?
Here's a real patient now.

95
00:03:28,308 --> 00:03:30,811
You're already
up by one.

96
00:03:32,913 --> 00:03:34,414
Anna?

97
00:03:35,549 --> 00:03:37,450
‐ 'Anna?'
‐ Hey, Carter.

98
00:03:37,483 --> 00:03:38,952
I'm running late.
Sorry.

99
00:03:38,985 --> 00:03:40,486
Oh, I must have read
your handwriting wrong.

100
00:03:40,521 --> 00:03:41,822
I thought it says 4D.

101
00:03:41,855 --> 00:03:44,390
It does. Here.
Come in.

102
00:03:44,424 --> 00:03:46,426
Oh.

103
00:03:46,459 --> 00:03:49,029
I had to get my shower in
before the guy in 4G.

104
00:03:49,062 --> 00:03:50,931
He stands in there
for, like, an hour

105
00:03:50,964 --> 00:03:52,633
listening to Howard Stern.

106
00:03:52,666 --> 00:03:54,801
Hey, can you give me a ride
to journal club tonight?

107
00:03:54,835 --> 00:03:55,836
Sure.

108
00:03:55,869 --> 00:03:58,438
Thanks.

109
00:03:58,471 --> 00:03:59,472
Make yourself comfortable.

110
00:03:59,506 --> 00:04:01,007
I'm gonna go
get dressed.

111
00:04:08,849 --> 00:04:11,417
This is a nice place.

112
00:04:11,451 --> 00:04:14,287
Please. It's a dump, but you
get what you pay for, right?

113
00:04:14,320 --> 00:04:15,556
What you gonna do?

114
00:04:15,589 --> 00:04:17,390
Especially on what
we get paid?

115
00:04:17,423 --> 00:04:19,359
'Right.'

116
00:04:19,392 --> 00:04:20,727
If you want, there's uh, some

117
00:04:20,761 --> 00:04:21,962
pop‐tarts on the counter.

118
00:04:29,369 --> 00:04:31,572
Can I, uh...make you one?

119
00:04:31,605 --> 00:04:33,874
No, it's okay.
I like them cold.

120
00:04:33,907 --> 00:04:34,908
Me, too.

121
00:04:34,941 --> 00:04:36,442
Really?

122
00:04:42,949 --> 00:04:43,950
Oh!

123
00:04:46,452 --> 00:04:48,421
Damn landlord won't
fumigate the place.

124
00:04:48,454 --> 00:04:51,558
I...write letters,
call the management office.

125
00:04:51,592 --> 00:04:53,026
You better believe
he doesn't have roaches

126
00:04:53,059 --> 00:04:55,428
around his fat‐cat estate
in Evanston.

127
00:04:55,461 --> 00:04:57,097
You know, you could report
him to the health department.

128
00:04:57,130 --> 00:04:58,599
Cockroaches are
a health hazard.

129
00:04:58,632 --> 00:05:00,967
Really? That really works?
You tried it?

130
00:05:01,001 --> 00:05:02,068
Yeah.

131
00:05:02,102 --> 00:05:03,837
Wow. I never would
have pegged you

132
00:05:03,870 --> 00:05:05,639
for a guy who knew
slumlord politics.

133
00:05:05,672 --> 00:05:07,841
You seem so milk‐fed
middle class.

134
00:05:07,874 --> 00:05:11,044
Well, you know my family
always had enough to get by.

135
00:05:11,077 --> 00:05:13,346
Uh, never went
hungry or anything.

136
00:05:13,379 --> 00:05:14,615
Hey, what do you say
we go over this

137
00:05:14,648 --> 00:05:16,382
journal stuff
at breakfast?

138
00:05:16,416 --> 00:05:19,385
I know a place that's got
a $1.99 pancake special.

139
00:05:19,419 --> 00:05:20,621
‐ You buying?
‐ My treat.

140
00:05:20,654 --> 00:05:23,089
Alright. Thanks.

141
00:06:19,145 --> 00:06:20,614
Get an AP lateral
on that knee.

142
00:06:20,647 --> 00:06:22,415
What happened to this guy?

143
00:06:22,448 --> 00:06:23,584
We were doing
a performance piece‐‐

144
00:06:23,617 --> 00:06:24,718
I was doing "William Tell's."

145
00:06:24,751 --> 00:06:26,419
An artist taking the risk

146
00:06:26,452 --> 00:06:27,988
as the average Philistine
is not willing to take.

147
00:06:28,021 --> 00:06:29,790
All this stupid idiot had to do

148
00:06:29,823 --> 00:06:32,058
is shoot the apple out
from in between my legs.

149
00:06:32,092 --> 00:06:33,594
You're lucky he
didn't aim higher.

150
00:06:33,627 --> 00:06:35,161
In a way, it makes it
even edgier, sir.

151
00:06:35,195 --> 00:06:36,196
You've shed blood
for your work.

152
00:06:36,229 --> 00:06:37,898
Are you Max Prole? Are you?

153
00:06:37,931 --> 00:06:40,166
No, no I'm sorry, it's just the
blood on the gallery wall

154
00:06:40,200 --> 00:06:41,835
made a bold splatter
and I‐I‐‐

155
00:06:41,868 --> 00:06:43,537
Do I look like
Jackson Pollock?

156
00:06:43,570 --> 00:06:45,739
I'm sorry, sir. I'm sorry.
I just, I‐I think this can work.

157
00:06:45,772 --> 00:06:47,473
Carol, let's give him
ten of morphine.

158
00:06:47,508 --> 00:06:49,009
Wait, I have an idea.

159
00:06:49,042 --> 00:06:51,011
The piece can go on and live
and breathe on its own.

160
00:06:51,044 --> 00:06:52,879
I will be the canvas.
No morphine.

161
00:06:52,913 --> 00:06:54,681
I want to experience
the sensations.

162
00:06:54,715 --> 00:06:58,118
Mr. Prole, you've a bullet hole
in your leg, now take the drug.

163
00:06:58,151 --> 00:06:59,452
Sorry, Carol.

164
00:06:59,485 --> 00:07:00,754
Score one for me.

165
00:07:03,524 --> 00:07:04,725
Hey, Shirley, do you know
where Dr. Hicks is

166
00:07:04,758 --> 00:07:05,759
doing her 8:00 A.M.
gastroplasty?

167
00:07:05,792 --> 00:07:06,893
‐ Did.
‐ Excuse me?

168
00:07:06,927 --> 00:07:07,928
She pushed it up to 6: 00.

169
00:07:07,961 --> 00:07:10,463
They should be done by now.

170
00:07:10,496 --> 00:07:11,665
Hey, what's going on?

171
00:07:11,698 --> 00:07:12,966
Just finishing
up my night.

172
00:07:12,999 --> 00:07:14,601
Dr. Hicks changed
her surgery?

173
00:07:14,635 --> 00:07:16,202
Yes, she had to make rounds
for Dr. Sloman.

174
00:07:16,236 --> 00:07:18,672
‐ You weren't here yet. So..
‐ Why wasn't I called?

175
00:07:18,705 --> 00:07:19,906
I didn't want
to disturb you.

176
00:07:19,940 --> 00:07:21,708
That was my gastroplasty.

177
00:07:21,742 --> 00:07:24,878
I know, but you have limited
time with your family, so..

178
00:07:24,911 --> 00:07:26,613
Is that what you
told Dr. Hicks?

179
00:07:26,647 --> 00:07:28,048
Peter, I thought I was
doing you a favor

180
00:07:28,081 --> 00:07:29,983
but if you're thinking
I wanted this surgery..

181
00:07:30,016 --> 00:07:31,752
Hey! Hey! Hey!
Whoa, whoa. Did you?

182
00:07:31,785 --> 00:07:34,120
Look, why don't you take my
ischemic bowel at 11:00

183
00:07:34,154 --> 00:07:35,856
and we'll call it a trade.

184
00:07:35,889 --> 00:07:37,591
Okay, yeah.
Why don't we do that?

185
00:07:37,624 --> 00:07:39,860
Good. You smell
of talcum powder.

186
00:07:39,893 --> 00:07:43,196
That's so sweet.

187
00:07:43,229 --> 00:07:44,264
‐ Hey, Jeanie.
‐ Hey.

188
00:07:44,297 --> 00:07:45,498
Your husband called.

189
00:07:45,532 --> 00:07:46,533
Did he leave a message?

190
00:07:46,567 --> 00:07:48,234
Yeah.
I wrote it down.

191
00:07:48,268 --> 00:07:50,571
"Mint juleps,
night blooming jasmine

192
00:07:50,604 --> 00:07:52,939
and warm southern breezes."

193
00:07:52,973 --> 00:07:54,140
‐ Oh. That was it?
‐ Yeah.

194
00:07:54,174 --> 00:07:55,208
I don't know what it means
but he sounds

195
00:07:55,241 --> 00:07:56,276
like a real romantic.

196
00:07:56,309 --> 00:07:57,578
Yeah, sometimes
I wish he wasn't

197
00:07:57,611 --> 00:07:58,912
as much of a romantic.

198
00:07:58,945 --> 00:08:00,681
Oh, you don't like being
swept off your feet?

199
00:08:00,714 --> 00:08:02,215
Uh, it's the landing
that's a problem.

200
00:08:02,248 --> 00:08:05,018
This Synergix group
has balanced budgets

201
00:08:05,051 --> 00:08:06,587
much deeper in the red
than ours.

202
00:08:06,620 --> 00:08:07,988
Yeah, I've made some
real progress.

203
00:08:08,021 --> 00:08:09,690
Oh, that's very laudable,
but I still think

204
00:08:09,723 --> 00:08:10,924
you should hear
what they have to say.

205
00:08:10,957 --> 00:08:12,125
What if I don't
like what I hear?

206
00:08:12,158 --> 00:08:13,727
I'd plan on liking it, Kerry.

207
00:08:13,760 --> 00:08:15,896
Otherwise, you can talk
to the board of directors.

208
00:08:15,929 --> 00:08:18,198
‐ Explain ER's massive deficit.
‐ I see.

209
00:08:18,231 --> 00:08:20,934
But they're looking for
scapegoats. Don't be one.

210
00:08:20,967 --> 00:08:22,536
It was a complete accident.
I promise.

211
00:08:22,569 --> 00:08:23,937
Mr. Prole made me do it.
He wanted me to do it

212
00:08:23,970 --> 00:08:25,205
‐ This is our guy.
‐ Dr. Greene.

213
00:08:25,238 --> 00:08:26,640
Come on, buddy.
Couple of questions.

214
00:08:26,673 --> 00:08:28,174
I told him I was a bad shot.

215
00:08:28,208 --> 00:08:30,544
‐ 'He wouldn't listen!'
‐ Got to love the crackpots.

216
00:08:30,577 --> 00:08:32,278
Could you cover me
for a few hours?

217
00:08:32,312 --> 00:08:34,915
Anspaugh's sending me
to some dog and pony show

218
00:08:34,948 --> 00:08:36,683
for these
ER management groups.

219
00:08:36,717 --> 00:08:37,751
If I have to.

220
00:08:37,784 --> 00:08:38,985
He just zeroed in
on every bit

221
00:08:39,019 --> 00:08:40,086
of flab
in the budget.

222
00:08:40,120 --> 00:08:41,187
Said we're overstaffed

223
00:08:41,221 --> 00:08:42,288
or doing too many tests.

224
00:08:42,322 --> 00:08:43,323
He wants the whole thing

225
00:08:43,356 --> 00:08:44,758
turned around yesterday.

226
00:08:44,791 --> 00:08:46,693
‐ Sounds bad.
‐ There's no money.

227
00:08:46,727 --> 00:08:48,895
Resources are stretched
as it is

228
00:08:48,929 --> 00:08:51,231
and he still wants me
to lose another 98,000.

229
00:08:51,264 --> 00:08:52,666
Something's
got to give.

230
00:08:52,699 --> 00:08:55,769
Yeah. It's just
I don't know what or who.

231
00:08:55,802 --> 00:08:57,971
Let me know
when you're back.

232
00:08:58,004 --> 00:08:59,039
What have you got?

233
00:08:59,072 --> 00:09:00,807
Matthew Lindermulder.

234
00:09:00,841 --> 00:09:02,776
His spotter at the gym
was asleep as the switch

235
00:09:02,809 --> 00:09:04,210
dropped a free‐weight bar
on his head.

236
00:09:04,244 --> 00:09:05,746
Ooh. I knew there
was a reason

237
00:09:05,779 --> 00:09:07,213
I let my gym
membership lapse.

238
00:09:07,247 --> 00:09:09,683
BP 120/80. Pulse 88.

239
00:09:09,716 --> 00:09:11,251
Pupils equal,
round and reactive.

240
00:09:11,284 --> 00:09:13,353
Uh, Babinski's
down going

241
00:09:13,386 --> 00:09:14,855
and he withdraws
to pain.

242
00:09:14,888 --> 00:09:17,157
Okay, let's get a CBC,
cross‐table c‐spine

243
00:09:17,190 --> 00:09:19,292
and a non‐contrast
head CT.

244
00:09:19,325 --> 00:09:20,326
Oh, man.

245
00:09:20,360 --> 00:09:21,862
'What's that?'

246
00:09:21,895 --> 00:09:23,129
It's a Klan tattoo.

247
00:09:25,932 --> 00:09:28,001
Danny, can you hear me?
How long was he seizing?

248
00:09:28,034 --> 00:09:30,270
His cellmate screamed
for us about an hour ago.

249
00:09:30,303 --> 00:09:31,371
He seized all the way
here and it stopped

250
00:09:31,404 --> 00:09:32,806
'just as we were pulling up.'

251
00:09:32,839 --> 00:09:35,275
‐ BP's 100/70. Pulse 100.
‐ Hmm.

252
00:09:37,210 --> 00:09:39,279
‐ Has he been here before?
‐ Don't know. I'm new.

253
00:09:39,312 --> 00:09:41,014
Wet himself in the van
on the way over.

254
00:09:41,047 --> 00:09:44,818
Okay. Look can you not use
