501
00:18:38,752 --> 00:18:40,821
I built a new life, Ms. Boulet.

502
00:18:40,854 --> 00:18:44,725
You don't believe
that's possible, do you?

503
00:18:44,758 --> 00:18:46,359
Sure, I do.

504
00:18:48,562 --> 00:18:50,731
Listen, we didn't really get a
chance to finish our discussion.

505
00:18:50,764 --> 00:18:53,466
Yeah, I think I heard everything
I need to hear, thank you.

506
00:18:53,499 --> 00:18:55,468
Oh, but I haven't.

507
00:18:55,502 --> 00:18:58,338
Listen, Kerry. I'm surrounded by
number crunchers all day long.

508
00:18:58,371 --> 00:19:01,341
When a confident, intelligent
and attractive woman

509
00:19:01,374 --> 00:19:02,543
walks through my door

510
00:19:02,576 --> 00:19:03,777
I must at least
try to ask her to lunch.

511
00:19:03,810 --> 00:19:05,912
Yeah, I have to
get back to work.

512
00:19:05,946 --> 00:19:07,480
No, no, no.
I'll make some calls.

513
00:19:07,514 --> 00:19:09,349
I'll tell Chicago
not to get sick for an hour.

514
00:19:09,382 --> 00:19:10,917
We can go down to the oak room
and I will tell you

515
00:19:10,951 --> 00:19:12,385
all my dirty
management secrets.

516
00:19:12,418 --> 00:19:15,689
What do you say?
Come on.

517
00:19:15,722 --> 00:19:17,490
Not to mention
the Japanese strain of staph

518
00:19:17,524 --> 00:19:20,293
that's resistant to
the most powerful antibiotics.

519
00:19:20,326 --> 00:19:21,728
Scary stuff.

520
00:19:21,762 --> 00:19:23,530
Hi, I'm Dr. Greene.

521
00:19:23,564 --> 00:19:24,865
Whoa.
What are you doing?

522
00:19:24,898 --> 00:19:26,366
There are germs, doctor.

523
00:19:26,399 --> 00:19:27,834
Uh‐ha. Well, you can
put that away now.

524
00:19:27,868 --> 00:19:29,335
Dr. Greene is
very sanitary.

525
00:19:29,369 --> 00:19:30,436
You don't have to worry.

526
00:19:30,470 --> 00:19:31,772
I'll be the judge
of that.

527
00:19:31,805 --> 00:19:33,540
Why don't we
take off the mask?

528
00:19:33,574 --> 00:19:35,776
This is a charcoal
particle filter mask.

529
00:19:35,809 --> 00:19:37,878
Twenty percent of people get
sicker in the hospital.

530
00:19:37,911 --> 00:19:40,647
I don't want to become
another statistic.

531
00:19:40,681 --> 00:19:44,585
So, you complain of fatigue,
dry mouth, shortness of breath.

532
00:19:44,618 --> 00:19:46,687
Heart rate's 130.
Resps 32.

533
00:19:46,720 --> 00:19:49,956
Ah, and you've been here before
for anxiety attacks.

534
00:19:49,990 --> 00:19:51,558
This is not
an anxiety attack.

535
00:19:51,592 --> 00:19:53,459
I'm allergic
to my apartment building.

536
00:19:53,493 --> 00:19:55,428
Why don't you move?

537
00:19:55,461 --> 00:19:58,331
Is that your medical
opinion, doctor?

538
00:19:58,364 --> 00:20:00,000
I have environmentally
based allergies.

539
00:20:00,033 --> 00:20:02,803
Or you're having some anxiety
and looking for attention.

540
00:20:02,836 --> 00:20:04,304
Mark!

541
00:20:04,337 --> 00:20:05,506
Why don't you
get a blood gas

542
00:20:05,539 --> 00:20:09,475
and call me
with the results.

543
00:20:09,510 --> 00:20:13,580
I see Dr. Corday handed you
off one nasty ileum.

544
00:20:13,614 --> 00:20:14,648
I'm just helping her out.

545
00:20:14,681 --> 00:20:16,850
Well, uh‐hm..

546
00:20:16,883 --> 00:20:20,453
I'm glad that you two
have some camaraderie.

547
00:20:20,486 --> 00:20:21,487
It'll come in handy

548
00:20:21,522 --> 00:20:23,023
with Dr. Romano.

549
00:20:23,056 --> 00:20:24,257
Excuse me?

550
00:20:24,290 --> 00:20:25,291
He's looking for

551
00:20:25,325 --> 00:20:26,326
another surgeon

552
00:20:26,359 --> 00:20:28,695
for his team, and, uh...

553
00:20:28,729 --> 00:20:29,963
I recommended you.

554
00:20:29,996 --> 00:20:33,667
Well, thank you, but..
Stapler.

555
00:20:33,700 --> 00:20:35,435
Thanks, but what?

556
00:20:35,468 --> 00:20:37,403
Well, I'm more interested
in working with surgeons

557
00:20:37,437 --> 00:20:38,539
who challenge my skills

558
00:20:38,572 --> 00:20:41,407
than dazzle me
with technology.

559
00:20:41,441 --> 00:20:43,409
Technology is
the new technique

560
00:20:43,443 --> 00:20:45,812
and if you don't master it,
somebody else will.

561
00:20:48,481 --> 00:20:51,752
When I saw how the flaws
in the system trickled down

562
00:20:51,785 --> 00:20:53,787
and affected the
day‐to‐day operations

563
00:20:53,820 --> 00:20:55,622
of an ER..

564
00:20:55,656 --> 00:20:57,524
I just knew I would be more
effective in management.

565
00:20:57,558 --> 00:20:58,925
And then you went back
and got your MBA?

566
00:20:58,959 --> 00:21:00,326
Yeah‐yeah‐yeah,
and then up

567
00:21:00,360 --> 00:21:01,895
the corporate ladder
and blah‐blah‐blah.

568
00:21:01,928 --> 00:21:04,598
Look, I didn't kidnap
you out of that conference

569
00:21:04,631 --> 00:21:07,467
to tell you my life story.

570
00:21:07,500 --> 00:21:09,469
I want to find out
more about you.

571
00:21:09,503 --> 00:21:12,639
Pick your brain
a little bit.

572
00:21:12,673 --> 00:21:14,708
Grapevine says you're doing
great things at County.

573
00:21:14,741 --> 00:21:16,510
I don't know about great.

574
00:21:16,543 --> 00:21:19,613
Ah, my spies tell me about
your waste reduction program.

575
00:21:19,646 --> 00:21:22,983
Yeah, well, saving a syringe
here and some gauze there

576
00:21:23,016 --> 00:21:25,819
is not the kind of dent
my bosses are looking for.

577
00:21:25,852 --> 00:21:27,353
Sounds serious.

578
00:21:27,387 --> 00:21:28,655
You want to bend my ear?

579
00:21:28,689 --> 00:21:30,056
Maybe I can help.

580
00:21:30,090 --> 00:21:31,558
Long story short.

581
00:21:31,592 --> 00:21:33,426
The board is convening
at the end of the week.

582
00:21:33,459 --> 00:21:34,995
‐ That's tomorrow.
‐ Yeah, don't remind me.

583
00:21:35,028 --> 00:21:37,430
And they need to cut ten percent
out of the budget immediately.

584
00:21:37,463 --> 00:21:39,032
We're already down
to the bone as it is.

585
00:21:39,065 --> 00:21:41,535
Are they making suggestions
or just handing you the axe?

586
00:21:41,568 --> 00:21:43,369
Well, they figure
I can chop eight percent

587
00:21:43,403 --> 00:21:45,539
by getting rid of half
of the physician's assistants.

588
00:21:45,572 --> 00:21:47,040
That's not a bad idea.

589
00:21:47,073 --> 00:21:49,009
On paper, maybe.

590
00:21:49,042 --> 00:21:51,044
Not so great if
you have to fire a friend.

591
00:21:53,013 --> 00:21:55,415
So this is about more
than just the bottom line.

592
00:21:56,983 --> 00:22:00,954
Well, it's never easy
letting people go, Kerry.

593
00:22:00,987 --> 00:22:04,090
But there are ways
to make it less painful..

594
00:22:04,124 --> 00:22:05,859
'...and sometimes
less permanent.'

595
00:22:07,828 --> 00:22:09,495
Shall we get some coffee?

596
00:22:11,732 --> 00:22:14,400
Sure. With what
I have waiting for me?

597
00:22:14,434 --> 00:22:16,970
I'm in no rush to get back.

598
00:22:17,003 --> 00:22:19,039
Carol, do you think people
are capable of change?

599
00:22:19,072 --> 00:22:21,007
Starting their lives over?

600
00:22:21,041 --> 00:22:22,909
Yeah, sure. Why not?

601
00:22:22,943 --> 00:22:25,979
I did. I used to have
nothing but deadbeat jobs

602
00:22:26,012 --> 00:22:28,615
and go out with loser guys
and...now look at me.

603
00:22:28,649 --> 00:22:30,817
Did a blood gas come up
on that germ lady?

604
00:22:30,851 --> 00:22:33,419
Uh, yeah. In curtain two.
Actually, Dr. Greene

605
00:22:33,453 --> 00:22:35,856
she seemed a little
upset when she left.

606
00:22:35,889 --> 00:22:37,624
Wanted to get out of here.

607
00:22:37,658 --> 00:22:39,092
So she left before
the test results?

608
00:22:39,125 --> 00:22:41,161
Uh, yeah. She made
a quick phone call and sprayed

609
00:22:41,194 --> 00:22:43,930
the entire receiver with
disinfectant and walked out.

610
00:22:43,964 --> 00:22:46,633
‐ She left AMA.
‐ 'Why would she do that?'

611
00:22:46,667 --> 00:22:48,034
I don't know.
Maybe because Mark was rude

612
00:22:48,068 --> 00:22:49,069
dismissive and patronizing.

613
00:22:49,102 --> 00:22:51,071
I'm sure
that's not true.

614
00:22:51,104 --> 00:22:52,839
It's not my job
to be their best friend.

615
00:22:52,873 --> 00:22:54,608
No, just their caregiver.

616
00:22:57,878 --> 00:22:59,580
What's all the brouhaha?

617
00:22:59,613 --> 00:23:01,181
Dr. Romano and
Dr. Corday are doing an

618
00:23:01,214 --> 00:23:03,784
osteochondral allograft.

619
00:23:03,817 --> 00:23:05,852
Well, hot damn.

620
00:23:05,886 --> 00:23:08,088
That's the first ever
here at County.

621
00:23:08,121 --> 00:23:09,923
Even had the Channel Five news
here covering it

622
00:23:09,956 --> 00:23:11,892
for their sci‐tech segment.

623
00:23:13,093 --> 00:23:15,562
See what I mean, Peter?

624
00:23:15,596 --> 00:23:17,998
The future...is now.

625
00:23:23,970 --> 00:23:25,939
Excuse me.

626
00:23:25,972 --> 00:23:27,741
‐ Excuse me.
‐ Oh, sorry.

627
00:23:27,774 --> 00:23:29,543
‐ Excuse me.
‐ Huh?

628
00:23:40,306 --> 00:23:42,523
Vincent Scarletti, 82,
found down in his bathroom

629
00:23:42,523 --> 00:23:44,157
He was in full arrest
on our arrival.

630
00:23:44,190 --> 00:23:47,460
We shocked him twice,
got a rhythm and a pulse.

631
00:23:47,493 --> 00:23:49,796
Mrs. Scarletti,
how long between the time

632
00:23:49,830 --> 00:23:51,698
that you found your husband
and the paramedics arrived?

633
00:23:51,732 --> 00:23:54,134
‐ W‐w‐what is that? What?
‐ She's hard of hearing.

634
00:23:54,167 --> 00:23:56,236
Mrs. Scarletti, how long was
your husband unconscious

635
00:23:56,269 --> 00:23:57,704
until the paramedics
showed up?

636
00:23:57,738 --> 00:24:00,707
Oh, I don't know.
Uh, ten minutes, 15 maybe.

637
00:24:00,741 --> 00:24:03,043
He was here two weeks ago.
They said he was just fine.

638
00:24:03,076 --> 00:24:04,244
We're going to do
everything we can.

639
00:24:04,277 --> 00:24:06,880
'On my count.
One, two, three.'

640
00:24:08,515 --> 00:24:11,818
‐ BP's 80/50.
‐ Pulse ox 90, pulse is 48.

641
00:24:11,852 --> 00:24:15,922
Alright. Start dopamine.
Titrate to a systolic of 100.

642
00:24:15,956 --> 00:24:18,491
Atropine 0.5 migs.

643
00:24:18,525 --> 00:24:20,561
His pupils
are fixed and dilated.

644
00:24:20,594 --> 00:24:23,597
No deep tendon reflexes.
Carol, get a CBC, chem‐7

645
00:24:23,630 --> 00:24:25,799
EKG, blood gas
and a portable chest.

646
00:24:25,832 --> 00:24:28,502
Lily, call respiratory.
Have them set up a vent.

647
00:24:28,535 --> 00:24:30,937
What is it?
What's wrong with my Vincenzo?

648
00:24:30,971 --> 00:24:32,739
It's okay, ma'am.
Please stand back.

649
00:24:32,773 --> 00:24:36,543
He's a good man. We have six
children and 11 grandchildren‐‐

650
00:24:36,577 --> 00:24:38,979
Mrs. Scarletti, you need
to wait outside.

651
00:24:39,012 --> 00:24:41,014
‐ I need to what?
‐ Carol, could I get an assist?

652
00:24:41,047 --> 00:24:42,916
Mrs. Scarletti, come on.
Let's go wait in the hall.

653
00:24:42,949 --> 00:24:44,885
Help him...

654
00:24:46,853 --> 00:24:48,622
‐ Carol?
‐ Mrs. Scarletti.

655
00:24:48,655 --> 00:24:51,692
Come on, we need to let the
doctor do his job. Come on.

656
00:24:51,725 --> 00:24:54,861
Come with me.

657
00:24:54,895 --> 00:24:56,863
'Have you seen Anspaugh?
He's late for a hot appy.'

658
00:24:56,897 --> 00:24:58,164
I think he's doing a AAA.

659
00:24:58,198 --> 00:25:01,568
Oh, those can slog on.
You got something juicy?

660
00:25:01,602 --> 00:25:04,037
‐ Yeah, hernia repair.
‐ Mine's a hot appendix.

661
00:25:04,070 --> 00:25:06,106
Still, they can't all
be newsworthy, eh?

662
00:25:06,139 --> 00:25:10,110
Unlike your osteochondral
allograph this afternoon, huh?

663
00:25:10,143 --> 00:25:12,546
You intentionally sidelined
me for that, didn't you?

664
00:25:12,579 --> 00:25:13,580
What?

665
00:25:13,614 --> 00:25:14,615
'Handed me off to Anspaugh'

666
00:25:14,648 --> 00:25:16,583
'so you could be with Romano.'

667
00:25:16,617 --> 00:25:18,785
That's the silliest
thing I've ever heard.

668
00:25:18,819 --> 00:25:22,055
He called me in to consult,
not the other way around.

669
00:25:22,088 --> 00:25:23,924
Hmm.

670
00:25:23,957 --> 00:25:25,592
If you say so.

671
00:25:25,626 --> 00:25:28,995
No. It's not just what I say.
That's the way it was.

672
00:25:29,029 --> 00:25:31,164
Do you know when Anspaugh
started the AAA?

673
00:25:31,197 --> 00:25:32,966
An hour ago.

674
00:25:32,999 --> 00:25:36,269
My patient's prepped.
I hate to get backed up.

675
00:25:36,302 --> 00:25:38,772
Yeah, you are busy today.

676
00:25:38,805 --> 00:25:41,942
Anspaugh wouldn't mind
if I just started, would he?

677
00:25:41,975 --> 00:25:44,210
It's painting by numbers.

678
00:25:44,244 --> 00:25:46,179
I haven't seen him mind yet.

679
00:25:50,884 --> 00:25:52,753
So you're okay finding another
ride to journal club tonight?

680
00:25:52,786 --> 00:25:53,820
Sure.

681
00:25:53,854 --> 00:25:55,188
I can still give you
a ride home.

682
00:25:55,221 --> 00:25:57,323
‐ No problem.
‐ I just totally spaced it.

683
00:25:57,357 --> 00:25:59,893
I agreed to have dinner
with my grandmother tonight.

684
00:25:59,926 --> 00:26:02,596
Hmm, so, uh, the hot dog's
just an appetizer?

685
00:26:02,629 --> 00:26:03,897
Uh, cooking is not
exactly something you‐‐

686
00:26:03,930 --> 00:26:06,299
Hey, Carter, Anna over here.

687
00:26:06,332 --> 00:26:10,604
Breathe, I can't breathe.
I can't breathe.

688
00:26:10,637 --> 00:26:11,905
Just relax. Hang on.
You're going to be okay.

689
00:26:11,938 --> 00:26:13,106
I'm going to take
this off now.

690
00:26:13,139 --> 00:26:14,941
‐ Okay?
‐ No, no! It's for my allergies.

691
00:26:14,975 --> 00:26:16,777
I already told
the other doctor.

692
00:26:16,810 --> 00:26:17,878
What other doctor?

693
00:26:17,911 --> 00:26:19,012
Come on, let's get a gurney.

694
00:26:19,045 --> 00:26:20,914
‐ Is that Mr. Scarletti?
‐ Yup.

695
00:26:20,947 --> 00:26:23,283
‐ Pretty advanced lung cancer.
‐ Did you pull up his records?

696
00:26:23,316 --> 00:26:24,985
Yeah, he was in two weeks ago.

697
00:26:25,018 --> 00:26:27,353
They told him the cancer had
spread and was now inoperable.

698
00:26:27,387 --> 00:26:30,023
‐ He never told his wife?
‐ Apparently not.

699
00:26:30,056 --> 00:26:32,092
‐ What's her name again?
‐ Margaret Scarletti.

700
00:26:32,125 --> 00:26:34,060
She's sitting over in chairs.
You want me to talk to her?

701
00:26:34,094 --> 00:26:35,295
I'll do it.

702
00:26:35,328 --> 00:26:38,198
Mark. Mark, I apologize
for being late.

703
00:26:38,231 --> 00:26:40,000
I had lunch
with a rep from Synergix

704
00:26:40,033 --> 00:26:41,201
and he had
some interesting ideas.

705
00:26:41,234 --> 00:26:43,003
We're slammed here.
So you're‐‐

706
00:26:43,036 --> 00:26:44,070
Mark, that crack‐head in three
is screaming his head off.

707
00:26:44,104 --> 00:26:45,171
He'll have to wait.

708
00:26:45,205 --> 00:26:46,406
I thought we could discuss

709
00:26:46,439 --> 00:26:48,208
the staffing situation
over at some point.

710
00:26:48,241 --> 00:26:49,976
Since it...
affects us both.

711
00:26:50,010 --> 00:26:51,778
Kerry, I don't really know what
the hell you're talking about.

712
00:26:51,812 --> 00:26:53,413
So why don't you write it down
in a memo and I 'll sign it?

713
00:26:53,446 --> 00:26:55,015
Dr. Greene, this woman
collapsed outside.

714
00:26:55,048 --> 00:26:56,783
‐ She said she saw you earlier.
‐ Yeah.

715
00:26:56,817 --> 00:26:58,351
It's probably anaphylactic
shock. I'll be right there.

716
00:26:58,384 --> 00:26:59,753
I'll get her.

717
00:26:59,786 --> 00:27:01,021
The back pain in two
wants more Demerol.

718
00:27:01,054 --> 00:27:02,322
‐ Yeah, in a minute.
‐ 'Hey, Mark..'

719
00:27:02,355 --> 00:27:03,690
Could you sign off
on this for me?

720
00:27:03,724 --> 00:27:05,025
‐ No. Not now.
‐ We could use the beds.

721
00:27:05,058 --> 00:27:06,693
What should I do
about the back pain?

722
00:27:06,727 --> 00:27:08,094
Well, why don't you
get Doyle to check him out.

723
00:27:08,128 --> 00:27:10,096
Dr. Greene, it's the hospital's
insurance attorney?

724
00:27:10,130 --> 00:27:11,331
Take a message.

725
00:27:13,299 --> 00:27:16,002
Mrs. Scarletti, could you
come with me, please?

726
00:27:16,036 --> 00:27:19,706
My husband, will he be okay?
Will he live? H‐how is he?

727
00:27:19,740 --> 00:27:22,008
I don't think we should
discuss this right here.

728
00:27:22,042 --> 00:27:23,977
What did you say?
Is he going to live?

729
00:27:24,010 --> 00:27:26,146
I said, we need
to find a place to talk.

730
00:27:26,179 --> 00:27:29,349
I'm so worried about Vincenzo.
Please, can I go see him?

731
00:27:29,382 --> 00:27:32,185
‐ No. No, no, no. Not‐not now.
‐ I just want to see how he is.

732
00:27:32,218 --> 00:27:35,088
Look, Mrs. Scarletti,
your husband has no chance

733
00:27:35,121 --> 00:27:36,356
for a meaningful recovery.

734
00:27:36,389 --> 00:27:39,726
He will recover okay?
Oh, thank you so much.

735
00:27:39,760 --> 00:27:41,227
No, no, no, no, no.

736
00:27:41,261 --> 00:27:43,129
I said, your husband
has no chance

737
00:27:43,163 --> 00:27:45,231
for a meaningful recovery.

738
00:27:45,265 --> 00:27:47,400
I‐I don't understand.
What are you saying?

739
00:27:47,433 --> 00:27:50,270
I'm saying that your
husband lied to you

740
00:27:50,303 --> 00:27:53,707
about his condition.
He's going to die.

741
00:28:00,781 --> 00:28:02,916
Jeanie, can you
explain‐explain it to her?

742
00:28:02,949 --> 00:28:04,985
Come on, come on.
Let's talk this one out.

743
00:28:07,487 --> 00:28:08,789
